<div class="content-page">
  <div class="content-page__inner">
    <h1 class="content-page__title">Parent Support Guide</h1>
    <p class="content-page__intro">You do not need a teaching background to use Math Direct. Every lesson includes a script that tells you exactly what to say. This guide covers what to expect and how to make the most of your sessions.</p>

    <div class="guide-section">
      <h2 class="guide-section__title">What to Expect</h2>
      <p>Math Direct teaches through short, structured lessons. You read a script, your child responds, and you give immediate feedback. Early lessons start with counting and number recognition. Over time, the lessons progress through addition, subtraction, place value, and mental math.</p>
      <p>Each lesson takes about 5&ndash;10 minutes. Most children complete one lesson per day. Some lessons may need to be repeated&mdash;that is completely normal and expected. The goal is mastery, not speed.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="guide-section">
      <h2 class="guide-section__title">Materials Needed</h2>
      <div class="guide-cards">
        <div class="guide-card">
          <h3 class="guide-card__title">A Device</h3>
          <p>Any phone, tablet, or computer with a web browser. No app download or installation required.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="guide-card">
          <h3 class="guide-card__title">An Adult</h3>
          <p>Math Direct is designed to be delivered by a parent, teacher, or tutor. The adult reads the script and guides the child through each step.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p style="margin-top:var(--space-md)">That is it. No workbooks, flashcards, or manipulatives are required, though pencil and paper can be helpful for practice.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="guide-section">
      <h2 class="guide-section__title">When to Practice</h2>
      <ul class="guide-tips">
        <li>Choose a consistent time each day. Morning, after school, or before bedtime&mdash;whatever works for your family.</li>
        <li>Keep sessions to 5&ndash;10 minutes. Short and focused is better than long and frustrating.</li>
        <li>Aim for daily practice. If you miss a day, pick up where you left off&mdash;no need to start over.</li>
        <li>Stop if your child is tired, upset, or distracted. Forced practice builds negative associations with math.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="guide-section">
      <h2 class="guide-section__title">How to Help</h2>
      <ul class="guide-tips">
        <li>Follow the script as written. The wording is intentional and tested.</li>
        <li>Be patient with errors. Correct gently, model the right answer, and move on.</li>
        <li>Celebrate effort, not just correct answers. "You worked hard on that" is powerful.</li>
        <li>Look for math in daily life. Counting stairs, splitting snacks equally, reading house numbers&mdash;all reinforce what your child is learning.</li>
        <li>Do not skip ahead. Each lesson builds on the previous one. Skipping creates gaps.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="guide-section">
      <h2 class="guide-section__title">Using the Dashboard</h2>
      <p>The <a href="/lessons/">Lessons page</a> doubles as a progress dashboard. As your child completes lessons, their progress is saved automatically in your browser using localStorage. No account or login is needed.</p>
      <p>You can export progress as a JSON file to back it up or transfer it to another device. Use the import button to restore saved progress. If you want to start fresh, the reset button clears all progress data.</p>
      <p><strong>Note:</strong> Progress is stored locally on your device. Clearing your browser data will erase it. Export regularly if you want to keep a backup.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="content-page__cta">
      <a href="/lessons/" class="btn btn--cta">Go to Lessons</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
